<HEADLINE>
Today's Rituxan infusion ended in sadness &amp; frustration
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Baraka &lt;truthnbea...@gmail.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-02T23:05:00 </POSTDATE>
Warm greetings of peace all,

I went into the Mt Zion infusion center with high hopes this morning -
they even managed to get the IV in on the first try, which almost
never happens! (Massive hydration the day before and following Tim's
advice to slap the sucker into a shape seemed to work! :)

They start off the IV at 50mg/per hour and then double it every 30
minutes until it is at 400 mg/per hour. However, I've never been able
to attain that rate. The first time especially I have allergic
reactions in the throat area so they have to slow it down
considerably, making it around a 10-hour infusion generally.

Anyway, when they reached 150 mg/hour I started getting the throat
tightening and tickles that I usually do and they stopped the IV and
administered more Benadryl. That usually calms everything down but
this time my chest tightened, I couldn't breathe and I thought I was
going to black out. There were about 6 nurses swarming around me
taking blood pressure, hooking me up to oxygen, shooting me up with
more Solumderol...it's all kind of a blur when I think about it and
very scary.

They stopped the infusion and paged my neuro 13 times over the next 2
hours. Unfortunately my neuro didn't respond to the pages, but another
doctor at the MS Clinic - who is not familiar with my case - did and
she told them to send me home without finishing the treatment and with
only 10% of the Rituxan used.

This is upsetting on so many levels...I am only approved for two
treatments by Blue Shield, of which this was one and which is now
incomplete with 90% of the drug wasted. Now I have to go back to my
neuro and see what he wants to do next. I assume he will want to
continue the infusions at slower rates but I don't know if insurance
will cover the extra treatment that will need to be scheduled in place
of this one. I think I am going to ask him to write some sort of
protocol so if he isn't available they can still follow his advice.

I'm also worried that I many be developing an increasing sensitivity
to Rituxan and afraid that over time I may not be able to take it any
more. But I'm trying not to even worry or think about that right now.

Has anyone else had treatment stopped or been taken off of Rituxan due
to allergic reactions? The doctor's advice seemed overly conservative
to me but I had no choice in the matter. In the past they've merely
waited for the reaction to subside and then started at a slower rate
again.

I'm exhausted and frustrated that this process has been lengthened and
really just want it to be over. Am praying for patience. Thanks for
all the best wishes on the other thread - I will let you know what my
neuro says next week.

Blessings, health and happiness to all!

Warmly,
Baraka
